            <div type="emblem" n="e38"><!-- Change the value of n to "e" followed by the number of the emblem. Use two digits for all numbers. -->
                <pb n="119"/><!-- Change to page number of the actual manuscript -->
                
                
                <div type="title" xml:lang="en">
                    <head>
                        <lb/><orig>Embleme</orig> 38. Of the Secrets of Nature.
                        <lb/>Rebis is, as Hermaphroditus, produced from the two moun
                        <lb break="no"/>tains of Mercury and Venus.
                    </head>
                </div>
                
                
                <div type="epigram" xml:lang="en">
                    <head><orig>Epigramme</orig> 38.</head>
                    <lg>
                        <l>Rebis is by the Ancients calld a <choice><orig>Twinne</orig><reg>Twin</reg></choice>,</l>
                        <l>Containing male and female sex therein:</l>
                        <l>For Hermes and Venus their Hermaphrodite</l>
                        <l>Is in two mountains <choice><orig>sayd</orig> to have birthright.</l>
                        <l>A double sex despite not, for a King</l>
                        <l>Will from the <choice><orig>selfe</orig> same man and woman spring.</l>
                    </lg>
                </div>
                
                
                <pb n="120"/> <!-- Change to page number of the actual manuscript -->
                <div type="discourse" xml:lang="en">
                    <head>Discourse 38.</head>
                    <ab><!--Our convention will be that if we have break = "no" then it means that the word is broken across the line with a dash--> 
                        <lb/>Socrates being demanded what Country man <choice><orig>hee</orig> was, answered a<pc>-</pc><milestone unit="section" n="e03-01" /> <!-- Change the value of n to "e" plus the number of the emblem (in two digits), followed by a hyphen and then a two-digit count of sentence -->
                        <lb/>Citizen of the world: by which his intention was signify, that though
                        <lb/><orig>hee</orig> was <choice><orig>borne</orig> at Athens as to person, yet in mind <choice><orig>hee</orig> freely beheld<pc>-</pc>
                        <lb/>the whole world, as his Country, and the things therein contained,<pc>-</pc>
                        <lb/>the whole earth being a wise mans Country, where <choice><orig>hee</orig> lives well:<pc>-</pc>
                        <lb/><orig>Soe</orig> if any one <choice><orig>aske</orig> the Philosophers what Countryman their<pc>-</pc>
                        <lb/>Hermaphrodite is, they answer, <choice><orig>hee</orig> belongs to the world, or is in all<pc>-</pc>
                        <lb/>corners of the world, where the Elements can be found, as the <choice><orig>Sonne</orig>
                        <lb/>of the wise, who <choice><orig>hath</orig> a country <choice><orig>coḿon</orig> with them: But <choice><orig>seing</orig> that
                        <lb/>it happens not that any man is <choice><orig>borne</orig> twice or oftener, nor first enters
                        <lb/>this light in <choice><orig>severall</orig> but in one place, as Socrates is owned to be an<pc>-</pc>
                        <lb/>Athenian, <choice><orig>soe</orig> is Rebis reputed an inhabiter of two mountains, that is,
                        <lb/>Mercury and Venus, from whence <choice><orig>allso</orig> the name of Hermaphrodite<pc>-</pc>
                        <lb/>given him by both parents; a noble and large country is indeed <choice><orig>noe</orig><pc>-</pc>
                        <lb/>small <choice><orig>helpe</orig><reg>help</reg></choice> to <choice><orig>doe</orig> things excellently well, in which Citizens are <choice><orig>præ
                        <lb break="no"/>ferrd</orig> before <choice><orig>forreigners</orig><reg>foreigners</reg></choice>, and promoted to <choice><orig>publicke</orig> offices, that they
                        <lb/>may not <choice><orig>lye</orig> in obscurity (as it happens in a <choice><orig>meane</orig> place, and <choice><orig>soe</orig>
                        <lb/>something of light come to them from the country) but <choice><orig>Shew</orig> them
                        <lb break="no"/>selves rather with their <choice><orig>owne</orig> virtues, even in the small <choice><orig>affaires</orig> of
                        <lb/>a house, and give light themselves to their <choice><orig>owne</orig> country: After this
                        <lb/>manner these mountains <choice><orig>unknowne</orig> to many men <choice><orig>doe</orig> acquire fame
                        <lb/>from the Herinaphrodite by reason of his illustrious actions, and name
                        <lb/>famous throughout the whole world. For who though never <choice><orig>soe</orig><pc>-</pc>
                        <lb/>little versed in the Philosophers <choice><orig>bookes</orig> <choice><orig>hath</orig> not <choice><orig>knowne</orig> Rebis?<pc>-</pc>
                        <lb/>Who <choice><orig>hath</orig> not seen or beheld <choice><orig>Androgynus</orig><reg>Androgynous</reg></choice> with two heads? <choice><orig>Hee</orig> verily
                        <lb/>has been <choice><orig>knowne</orig> to the <choice><orig>Indyes</orig><reg>Indies</reg></choice> themselves, and his fame <choice><orig>hath</orig> been<pc>-</pc>
                        <lb/>dispersed farther, than the fame even of King Alexander: Many<pc>-</pc>
                        <lb/>men <choice><orig>doe</orig> <choice><orig>travell</orig> out of <choice><orig>farre</orig> <choice><orig>countryes</orig> to see and discourse some
                        <lb/>learned man, or otherwise <choice><orig>remarkeable</orig><reg>remarkable</reg></choice> for singular military in
                        <lb break="no"/>dustry, art or science, but many more will betake themselves to<pc>-</pc>
                        <lb/>the <choice><orig>sayd</orig> Mountains of Rebis, provided they can <choice><orig>learne</orig> where<pc>-</pc>
                        <lb/>they may be found: With how great study and care did Morienus<pc>-</pc>
                        <lb/>being departed from Rome <choice><orig>seeke</orig> and at length find Adferus Alexan
                        <lb break="no"/>drinus, <choice><orig>hee</orig> <choice><orig>himselfe</orig> declares in his <choice><orig>booke</orig>, and therefore was to be<pc>-</pc>
                        <lb/>esteemed more happy, and acceptable to God, in that <choice><orig>hee</orig> had from a<pc>-</pc>
                        <lb/>living teacher, and not from <choice><orig>dumbe</orig><reg>dumb</reg></choice> masters learnt, and beheld this
                        <lb/>thing, that is, the native place of Rebis; <choice><orig>noe</orig> <choice><orig>lesse</orig> assiduity and<pc>-</pc>
                        <lb/>diligence ought they to use, who <choice><orig>seeke</orig> the country of Rebis by<pc>-</pc>
                        <lb/>themselves, being informed by reason, and the documents of books:
                        <lb/>But though some books may sometimes seem to be clear and conspi
                        
                        
                        
                        <pb n="121"/><fw>Discourse 38.</fw><!-- Page number of the actual manuscript, followed by the header on the page. -->
                        <lb break="no"/>cuous, yet they are <choice><orig>soe</orig> <choice><orig>veild</orig><reg>veiled</reg></choice> and clouded with intricacy and ob
                        <lb break="no"/>scurity, that by reason thereof it is very difficult to make distinction:
                        <lb/>Wherefore <choice><orig>wee</orig> must cautiously proceed with them, that they, which are
                        <lb/><orig>præpard</orig> for remedy, may not be usd for <choice><orig>poyson</orig>: They are certainly<pc>-</pc>
                        <lb/>a vast ocean, in which expert mariners <choice><orig>sayling</orig><reg>sailing</reg></choice> may by <choice><orig>Astronomi
                        <lb break="no"/>call</orig><reg>Astronomical</reg></choice> instruments know the latitude, or elevation of the <choice><orig>Æquator</orig><reg>Equator</reg></choice> above
                        <lb/>the Horizon, the Magnet <choice><orig>Shewing</orig> the North pole, but by <choice><orig>noe</orig> means
                        <lb/>the longitude, or how great an <choice><orig>internall</orig> of degrees they are distant<pc>-</pc>
                        <lb/>from the first Meridian, which is next to the fortunate Islands; <choice><orig>soe</orig><pc>-</pc>
                        <lb/>that they are <choice><orig>uncertaine</orig> in what place they may be between west<pc>-</pc>
                        <lb/>and east: What therefore is here to be done? That which the same<pc>-</pc>
                        <lb/>Mariners use to <choice><orig>doe</orig>, consult experience with reason, and thereby<pc>-</pc>
                        <lb/><orig>learne</orig> how to determine a long voyage by particular signs, <choice><orig>promon
                        <lb break="no"/>toryes</orig><reg>promontories</reg></choice>, Islands, and other things, that they may not for want of consi
                        <lb break="no"/>deration fall upon Sands and rocks: But here is <choice><orig>lesse</orig> danger, if the
                        <lb/>thing prosper not, but if <choice><orig>soe</orig>, greater <choice><orig>gaine</orig>, than there, where goods<pc>-</pc>
                        <lb/>and life are lost in an <choice><orig>houre</orig>: But the <choice><orig>mountaine</orig> of the <choice><orig>Philoso
                        <lb break="no"/>phicall</orig> Mercury is not Nonacris, nor Atlas, where sometimes it is reported
                        <lb/>to be brought forth, but Parnassus with two tops, in one of which<pc>-</pc>
                        <lb/>Hermes, in the other Venus resides: <choice><orig>Hee</orig> <choice><orig>allso</orig> is Apollo with the Mu
                        <lb break="no"/>ses, and Hippocrene, the <choice><orig>fountaine</orig> of Pegasus, with <choice><orig>laurell</orig><reg>laurel</reg></choice> <choice><orig>allwayes</orig>
                        <lb/>green: it is one <choice><orig>mountaine</orig> by name, but really two, as Hermaphro
                        <lb break="no"/>ditus is beheld with two heads, and two members in one body: But<pc>-</pc>
                        <lb/>what man of a thousand persists in ascending to the top of this<pc>-</pc>
                        <lb/><orig>mountaine</orig>? Who dos not begin to <choice><orig>hæsitate</orig><reg>hesitate</reg></choice> at the <choice><orig>bottome</orig> being<pc>-</pc>
                        <lb/>impeded by I know not what obstacles? Whoever<!-- he splits the word here. How to code? --> attaines to the<pc>-</pc>
                        <lb/><orig>midle</orig> of it? for <quote rend="indent"><lg xml:lang="lat"><l>Non levis ascensus, si quis petat ardua, sudor</l>
                                <l>Plurimus hunc tollit, nocturnæ insomnis olive</l>
                                <l>Immoritur, delet, quod mox laudaverat in se,</l>
                                <l>Qui cupit æternæ donari frondis honore.</l>
                            </lg>
                        </quote>
                        <lb/>Wherefore it is <choice><orig>noe</orig> strange thing, if <choice><orig>onely</orig> one of <choice><orig>tenne</orig> thousand un
                        <lb break="no"/>dertake these Herculean <choice><orig>labours</orig>, <choice><orig>soe</orig> as to <choice><orig>sett</orig> foot on the top of the
                        <lb/><orig>mountaine</orig>, and enjoy the <choice><orig>immortall</orig><reg>immortal</reg></choice> reward of a <choice><orig>laurell</orig><reg>laurel</reg></choice> garland,
                        <lb/>which that all those that are upright, docible, and addicted to vir
                        <lb break="no"/>tue and learning may receive with joy, but the <choice><orig>vaine</orig><reg>vain</reg></choice> and envi
                        <lb break="no"/>ous <choice><orig>depriv'd</orig><reg>deprived</reg></choice> thereof, is much to be desired<pc>. . . . . . .</pc>
                    </ab>   
                </div>
                
            </div>
